The grilled cheese toaster thing works but it depends on the type of toaster and the timing mechanism.

Toasters will use two general types of timers. One is an electronic timer where a circuit basically pops a solenoid after a certain amount of time and the other is heat causing something to expand to a point it trips a latch that allows it to pop.

The best is the ones that use wax motors in my opinion. But there are generally arrows or something pointing to a certain side in the non electronic timer ones that indicates the side you are to use when toasting just one piece of bread. This is because it needs the airflow in the slot to be restricted to some degree in order for the heat near the bottom to build up enough to trigger the release from that particular side.

Anyways, not all of these will work properly on their sides depending on the location of the heat affected device. But if it does, use that side and it should produce some of the crapiest grilled cheese sandwiches you ever had. It's just one step above putting cheese on toast and microwaving it. Set the resistor or darkness knob to light. You can help it a tiny bit by using the spray margarine but use sparingly because it can drip onto the elements and smoke a lot.
